# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: operational-amplifiers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] In electronics, a **chopper** circuit is any of numerous types of electronic switching devices and circuits used in power control and signal applications.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] A chopper is a device that converts fixed DC input to a variable DC output voltage directly.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Essentially, a chopper is an electronic switch that is used to interrupt one signal under the control of another.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] In power electronics applications, since the switching element is either fully on or fully off, its losses are low and the circuit can provide high efficiency.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] However, the current supplied to the load is discontinuous and may require smoothing or a high switching frequency to avoid undesirable effects.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] In signal processing circuits, use of a chopper stabilizes a system against drift of electronic components; the original signal can be recovered after amplification or other processing by a synchronous demodulator that essentially un-does the "chopping" process.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] For all the chopper configurations operating from a fixed DC input voltage, the average value of the output voltage is controlled by periodic opening and closing of the switches used in the chopper circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] In pulse-width modulation the switches are turned on at a constant chopping frequency.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The total time period of one cycle of output waveform is constant.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The average output voltage is directly proportional to the ON time of chopper.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The ratio of ON time to total time is defined as duty cycle.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] It can be varied between 0 and 1 or between 0 and 100%.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Pulse-width modulation (PWM), or pulse-duration modulation (PDM), is a technique used to encode a message into a pulsing signal.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Although this modulation technique can be used to encode information for transmission, its main use is to allow the control of the power supplied to electrical devices, especially to inertial loads such as motors.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The average value of voltage (and current) fed to the load is controlled by turning the switch between supply and load on and off at a fast rate.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The longer the switch is on compared to the off periods, the higher the total power supplied to the load.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The PWM switching frequency has to be much higher than what would affect the load (the device that uses the power), which is to say that the resultant waveform perceived by the load must be as smooth as possible.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Typically switching has to be done several times a minute in an electric stove, 120 Hz in a lamp dimmer, from few kilohertz (kHz) to tens of kHz for a motor drive and well into the tens or hundreds of kHz in audio amplifiers and computer power supplies.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] In frequency modulation, pulses of a fixed amplitude and duration are generated and the average value of output is adjusted by changing how often the pulses are generated.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Variable pulse width and frequency combines both changes in the pulse width and repetition rate.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] In current limit control (CLC) technique, duty cycle is controlled by controlling the load current between maximum and minimum values.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The chopper is switched ON and OFF periodically so that the load current is maintained between predetermined maximum and minimum values.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] One classic use for a chopper circuit and where the term is still in use is in *chopper amplifiers*.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Some types of signals that need amplifying can be so small that an incredibly high gain is required, but very high gain DC amplifiers are much harder to build with low offset and $1/f$ noise, and reasonable stability and bandwidth.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] It's much easier to build an AC amplifier instead.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] A chopper circuit is used to break up the input signal so that it can be processed as if it were an AC signal, then integrated back to a DC signal at the output.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] In this way, extremely small DC signals can be amplified.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] This approach is often used in electronic instrumentation where stability and accuracy are essential; for example, it is possible using these techniques to construct pico-voltmeters and Hall sensors.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The input offset voltage of amplifiers becomes important when trying to amplify small signals with very high gain.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Because this technique creates a very low input offset voltage amplifier, and because this input offset voltage does not change much with time and temperature, these techniques are also called "zero-drift" amplifiers (because there is no drift in input offset voltage with time and temperature).
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Related techniques that also give these zero-drift advantages are auto-zero and chopper-stabilized amplifiers.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Auto-zero amplifiers use a secondary auxiliary amplifier to correct the input offset voltage of a main amplifier.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Chopper-stabilized amplifiers use a combination of auto-zero and chopper techniques to give some excellent DC precision specifications.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Some example chopper and auto-zero amplifiers are LTC2050, MAX4238/MAX4239 and OPA333.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Take a general step-up chopper with voltage source $V_{s}$ which is in series with the inductor L , diode and the load with average voltage $V_{ave}$ .
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The chopper switch would be in parallel with the series diode and load.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Whenever the chopper switch is on, the output is shorted.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] where $T_{ON}$ is the time were a load voltage is present and $\Delta i$ the change current with respect to $T_{ON}$ .
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] where $T_{OFF}$ is the time were a load voltage is zero.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] where $V_{ave}$ is the average output voltage.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Taking a general step-down chopper with voltage source $V_{s}$ which is in series with the chopper switch, inductor, and the load with voltage $V_{o}$ .
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The diode would be in parallel with the series inductor and load.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] where $V_{ave}$ is the average output voltage, $\alpha$ is the duty cycle and $V_{s}$ is the source voltage.
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] Taking a general buck-boost chopper which works as stepup and down chopper, let the voltage source $V_{s}$ be in series with the chopper switch, reverse biased diode, and the load with voltage $V_{o}$ .
[src:operational-amplifiers/chopper-electronics] The inductor would be in parallel with the series diode and load.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] A **differential amplifier** is a type of electronic amplifier that amplifies the difference between two input voltages but suppresses any voltage common to the two inputs.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Single amplifiers are usually implemented by either adding the appropriate feedback resistors to a standard op-amp, or with a dedicated integrated circuit containing internal feedback resistors.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] It is also a common sub-component of larger integrated circuits handling analog signals.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In practice, however, the gain is not quite equal for the two inputs.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] This means, for instance, that if $V_{\text{in}}^{+}$ and $V_{\text{in}}^{-}$ are equal, the output will not be zero, as it would be in the ideal case.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] where $A_{\text{c}}$ is called the common-mode gain of the amplifier.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] As differential amplifiers are often used to null out noise or bias voltages that appear at both inputs, a low common-mode gain is usually desired.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The common-mode rejection ratio (CMRR), usually defined as the ratio between differential-mode gain and common-mode gain, indicates the ability of the amplifier to accurately cancel voltages that are common to both inputs.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In a perfectly symmetric differential amplifier, $A_{\text{c}}$ is zero, and the CMRR is infinite.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Note that a differential amplifier is a more general form of amplifier than one with a single input; by grounding one input of a differential amplifier, a single-ended amplifier results.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Modern differential amplifiers are usually implemented with a basic two-transistor circuit called a *“long-tailed” pair* or *differential pair*.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] This circuit was originally implemented using a pair of vacuum tubes.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The circuit works the same way for all three-terminal devices with current gain.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The bias points of “long-tail” resistor circuit are largely determined by Ohm's law and less so by active-component characteristics.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The long-tailed pair was developed from earlier knowledge of push–pull circuit techniques and measurement bridges.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] An early circuit which closely resembles a long-tailed pair was published by British neurophysiologist Bryan Matthews in 1934, and it seems likely that this was intended to be a true long-tailed pair but was published with a drawing error.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The earliest definite long-tailed pair circuit appears in a patent submitted by Alan Blumlein in 1936.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] By the end of the 1930s the topology was well established and had been described by various authors, including Frank Offner (1937), Otto Schmitt (1937) and Jan Friedrich Toennies (1938), and it was particularly used for detection and measurement of physiological impulses.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The long-tailed pair was very successfully used in early British computing, most notably the Pilot ACE model and descendants, Maurice Wilkes’ EDSAC, and probably others designed by people who worked with Blumlein or his peers.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] One disadvantage is that the output voltage swing (typically ±10–20 V) was imposed upon a high DC voltage (200 V or so), requiring care in signal coupling, usually some form of wide-band DC coupling.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Many computers of this time tried to avoid this problem by using only AC-coupled pulse logic, which made them very large and overly complex (ENIAC: 18,000 tubes for a 20-digit calculator) or unreliable.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] DC-coupled circuitry became the norm after the first generation of vacuum-tube computers.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] A differential (long-tailed, emitter-coupled) pair amplifier consists of two amplifying stages with common (emitter, source or cathode) degeneration.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] With two inputs and two outputs, this forms a differential amplifier stage (Figure 2).
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The two bases (or grids or gates) are inputs which are differentially amplified (subtracted and multiplied) by the transistor pair; they can be fed with a differential (balanced) input signal, or one input could be grounded to form a phase splitter circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] An amplifier with differential output can drive a floating load or another stage with differential input.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] If the differential output is not desired, then only one output can be used (taken from just one of the collectors (or anodes or drains), disregarding the other output; this configuration is referred to as *single-ended output*.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The gain is half that of the stage with differential output.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] To avoid sacrificing gain, a differential to single-ended converter can be utilized.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] This is often implemented as a current mirror (Figure 3, below).
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The emitter-coupled amplifier is compensated for temperature drifts, VBE is cancelled, and the Miller effect and transistor saturation are avoided.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] That is why it is used to form emitter-coupled amplifiers (avoiding Miller effect), phase splitter circuits (obtaining two inverse voltages), ECL gates and switches (avoiding transistor saturation), etc.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] To explain the circuit operation, four particular modes are isolated below although, in practice, some of them act simultaneously and their effects are superimposed.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In contrast with classic amplifying stages that are biased from the side of the base (and so they are highly β-dependent), the differential pair is directly biased from the side of the emitters by sinking/injecting the total quiescent current.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The series negative feedback (the emitter degeneration) makes the transistors act as voltage stabilizers; it forces them to adjust their VBE voltages (base currents) to pass the quiescent current through their collector-emitter junctions.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] So, due to the negative feedback, the quiescent current depends only slightly on the transistor's β.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The biasing base currents needed to evoke the quiescent collector currents usually come from the ground, pass through the input sources and enter the bases.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] So, the sources have to be galvanic (DC) to ensure paths for the biasing current and low resistive enough to not create significant voltage drops across them.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Otherwise, additional DC elements should be connected between the bases and the ground (or the positive power supply).
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In common mode (the two input voltages change in the same directions), the two voltage (emitter) followers cooperate with each other working together on the common high-resistive emitter load (the "long tail").
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] They all together increase or decrease the voltage of the common emitter point (figuratively speaking, they together "pull up" or "pull down" it so that it moves).
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In addition, the dynamic load "helps" them by changing its instant ohmic resistance in the same direction as the input voltages (it increases when the voltage increases and vice versa.) thus keeping up constant total resistance between the two supply rails.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] There is a full (100%) negative feedback; the two input base voltages and the emitter voltage change simultaneously while the collector currents and the total current do not change.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] As a result, the output collector voltages do not change as well.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The collector resistors can be replaced by a current mirror (the top blue section in Fig.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] 3), whose output part acts as an active load.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Thus the differential collector current signal is converted to a single-ended voltage signal without the intrinsic 50% losses, so the gain is doubled.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] This is achieved by copying the input collector current from the left to the right side, where the magnitudes of the two input signals add.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] For this purpose, the input of the current mirror is connected to the left output, and the output of the current mirror is connected to the right output of the differential amplifier.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The current mirror copies the left collector current and passes it through the right transistor that produces the right collector current.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] At this right output of the differential amplifier, the two signal currents (pos. and neg. current changes) are subtracted.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In this case (differential input signal), they are equal and opposite.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Thus, the difference is twice the individual signal currents (Δ*I* − (−Δ*I*) = 2Δ*I*), and the differential to single-ended conversion is completed without gain losses.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] 4 shows the transmission characteristic of this circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The quiescent current has to be constant to ensure constant collector voltages at common mode.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] This requirement is not so important in the case of a differential output, since although their two collector voltages will vary simultaneously their difference (the output voltage) will not vary.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] But in the case of a single-ended output, it is extremely important to keep a constant current since the output collector voltage will vary.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Thus the higher the resistance of the current source $R_{\text{e}}$ in the original circuit of Fig.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] 2, the lower (better) is the common-mode gain $A_{\text{c}}$ .
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The constant current needed could be produced by connecting an element (resistor) with very high resistance between the shared emitter node and the supply rail (negative for NPN and positive for PNP transistors), but that requires a high supply voltage.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] So in more sophisticated designs, an element with high differential (dynamic) resistance approximating a constant current source/sink (the bottom of Fig.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] It is usually implemented by a current mirror because of its high compliance voltage (small voltage drop across the output transistor).
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] It is possible to connect a floating source between the two bases, but it is necessary to ensure paths for the biasing base currents.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In the case of galvanic source, only one resistor has to be connected between one of the bases and the ground.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The biasing current will enter directly this base and indirectly (through the input source) the other one.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] If the source is capacitive, two resistors have to be connected between the two bases and the ground to ensure different paths for the base currents.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The input impedance of the differential pair highly depends on the input mode.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] At common mode, the two parts behave as common-collector stages with high emitter loads; so, the input impedances are extremely high.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] At differential mode, they behave as common-emitter stages with grounded emitters; so, the input impedances are low.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The output impedance of the differential pair is high (especially for the improved differential pair with a current mirror as shown in Figure 3).
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The common-mode input voltage can vary between the two supply rails but cannot closely reach them since some voltage drops (minimum 1 volt) have to remain across the output transistors of the two current mirrors.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] An operational amplifier, or op-amp, is a differential amplifier with very high differential-mode gain, very high input impedance, and low output impedance.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] An op-amp differential amplifier can be built with predictable and stable gain by applying *negative* feedback (Figure 5).
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Some kinds of differential amplifier usually include several simpler differential amplifiers.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] For example, a fully differential amplifier, an instrumentation amplifier, or an isolation amplifier are often built from a combination of several op-amps.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Differential amplifiers are found in many circuits that utilize series negative feedback (op-amp follower, non-inverting amplifier, etc.), where one input is used for the input signal, the other for the feedback signal (usually implemented by operational amplifiers).
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] For comparison, the old-fashioned inverting single-ended op-amps from the early 1940s could realize only parallel negative feedback by connecting additional resistor networks (an op-amp inverting amplifier is the most popular example).
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] A common application is for the control of motors or servos, as well as for signal amplification applications.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In discrete electronics, a common arrangement for implementing a differential amplifier is the long-tailed pair, which is also usually found as the differential element in most op-amp integrated circuits.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] A long-tailed pair can be used as an analog multiplier with the differential voltage as one input and the biasing current as another.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] A differential amplifier is used as the input stage emitter coupled logic gates and as switch.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] When used as a switch, the "left" base/grid is used as signal input and the "right" base/grid is grounded; output is taken from the right collector/plate.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] When the input is zero or negative, the output is close to zero (but can be not saturated); when the input is positive, the output is most-positive, dynamic operation being the same as the amplifier use described above.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The differential amplifier is used in the cathode follower oscillator.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] The advantages are high impedance of the differential amplifier input and output and small phase shift between input and output.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] This application uses only one input and one output of the differential amplifier.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In case the operational amplifier's (non-ideal) input bias current or differential input impedance are a significant effect, one can select a feedback network that improves the effect of common-mode input signal and bias.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] In Figure 6, current generators model the input bias current at each terminal; *I*+b and *I*−b represent the input bias current at terminals *V*+ and *V*− respectively.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] which implies that the closed-loop gain for the differential signal is *V*+in − *V*−in, but the common-mode gain is identically zero.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] It also implies that the common-mode input bias current has cancelled out, leaving only the input offset current *I*Δb = *I*+b − *I*−b still present, and with a coefficient of *R*i.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] It is as if the input offset current is equivalent to an input offset voltage acting across an input resistance *R*i, which is the source resistance of the feedback network into the input terminals.
[src:operational-amplifiers/differential-amplifier] Finally, as long as the open-loop voltage gain *A*ol is much larger than unity, the closed-loop voltage gain is *R*f/*R*i, the value one would obtain through the rule-of-thumb analysis known as "virtual ground".
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The **operational amplifier integrator** is an electronic integration circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Based on the operational amplifier (op-amp), it performs the mathematical operation of integration with respect to time; that is, its output voltage is proportional to the input voltage integrated over time.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The typical circuit, and its common name, is a form of the **Miller integrator**, but based on an op-amp.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The circuit is mostly used in analog computers, analog-to-digital converters and wave-shaping circuits.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] A common wave-shaping use is as a charge amplifier and they are usually constructed using an operational amplifier though they can use high gain discrete transistor configurations.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The input current is offset by a negative feedback current flowing in the capacitor, which is generated by an increase in output voltage of the amplifier.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The output voltage is therefore dependent on the value of input current it has to offset and the inverse of the value of the feedback capacitor.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The greater the capacitor value, the less output voltage has to be generated to produce a particular feedback current flow.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The input capacitance of the circuit is almost zero because of the Miller effect.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] This ensures that the stray capacitances (the cable capacitance, the amplifier input capacitance, etc.) are virtually grounded and have no influence on the output signal.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Referring to the above diagram, if the op-amp is assumed to be ideal, then the voltage at the inverting (-) input is held equal to the voltage at the non-inverting (+) input as a virtual ground.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The input voltage passes a current $V_{\text{in}}/{R_{1}}$ through the resistor producing a compensating current flow through the series capacitor to maintain the virtual ground.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] This charges or discharges the capacitor over time.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Because the resistor and capacitor are connected to a virtual ground, the input current does not vary with capacitor charge, so a linear integration that works across all frequencies is achieved (unlike RC circuit § Integrator).
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Real op-amps have a finite open-loop gain, an input offset voltage $(V_{\text{OS}})$ and input bias currents $(I_{\text{B}})$ , which may not be well-matched and may be distinguished as $I_{\text{B-}}$ going into the inverting input and $I_{\text{B+}}$ going into the non-inverting input.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] This can cause several issues for the ideal design; most importantly, if $V_{\text{in}}=0$ , both the output offset voltage and the input bias current $I_{\text{B-}}$ can cause current to pass through the capacitor, causing the output voltage to drift over time until the op-amp saturates.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Similarly, if $V_{\text{in}}$ were a signal centered about zero volts (i.e. without a DC component), no drift would be expected in an ideal circuit, but may occur in a real circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Well-matched input bias currents then cause the same voltage drop of $R_{1}I_{\text{B}}$ at both the inverting and non-inverting terminals, to effectively cancel out the effect of bias current at those inputs.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] A CMOS op amp should be selected to minimize errors from input bias current, since MOSFET gates don't require DC current and only have small leakage current on the order of picoamps (pA).
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Also, in a DC steady state, an ideal capacitor acts as an open circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The DC gain of the ideal circuit is therefore infinite (or in practice, the open-loop gain of a non-ideal op-amp).
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Any DC (or very low frequency) component may then cause the op amp output to drift into saturation.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] To prevent this, the DC gain can be limited to a finite value by inserting a large resistor $R_{\text{F}}$ in parallel with the feedback capacitor.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Note that some op amps have a large internal feedback resistor, and many real capacitors have leakage that is effectively a large feedback resistor.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] There are other methods, which may be combined, to deal with offset error.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] A variation of this circuit simply uses an adjustable voltage source instead of $R_{\text{om}}$ and some op amps with very low offset voltage may not even require offset correction.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Offset correction is a bigger concern for older op amps, particularly BJT types.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Another variation circuit to avoid offset correction that works for AC signals only is to capacitively-couple the input with a large input capacitor before $R_{1}$ which will naturally charge up to the offset voltage.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Additionally, because offset may drift over time and temperature, some op amps provide null offset pins, which can be connected to a potentiometer whose wiper connects to the negative supply to allow readjusting when conditions change.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] It should also be noted that the integrator is commonly used as part of a feedback/servo loop which provides the DC feedback path, removing the need for a feedback resistor.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] But the overall frequency response of the two circuits differ due to their different pole locations.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The ideal integrator's transfer function ${\tfrac {1}{s}}$ corresponds to the time-domain integration property of the Laplace transform.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Since its denominator is just s , the transfer function has a pole frequency at $f{=}0$ .
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Thus its frequency response has a steady -20 dB per decade slope across all frequencies and appears as a downward-sloping line in a Bode plot.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] The frequency response has a relatively constant gain up to $f_{\text{cutoff}}$ , and then decreases by 20 dB per decade.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] While this circuit is no longer an integrator for low frequencies around and below $f_{\text{cutoff}}$ , the error is decreases to only 0.5% at one decade above $f_{\text{cutoff}}$ and the response approaches that of an ideal integrator as the frequency increases.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Real op amps also have a limited gain-bandwidth product (GBWP), which adds an additional high frequency pole.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp-integrator] Integration only occurs along the -20 dB per decade slope, which is steady only from frequencies about a decade above $f_{\text{cutoff}}$ to about a decade below the op amp's GBWP.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] An **operational amplifier** (often **op amp**, **op-amp**, or **opamp**) is a DC-coupled electronic amplifier with a differential input, a (usually) single-ended output voltage, and an extremely high gain.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Its name comes from its original use of performing mathematical operations in analog computers.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The **voltage-feedback opamp** (**VFOA** or **VFA**, the focus of this article) amplifies the voltage difference between its two inputs, while the less common *current-feedback op amp* (CFOA) amplifies the current between its two inputs.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] By using negative feedback, the characteristics of an op amp application circuit (e.g., its gain, input and output impedance, bandwidth, and functionality) can be determined by external components and have little dependence on temperature coefficients or engineering tolerance in the op amp itself.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] This flexibility has made the op amp a popular building block in analog circuits.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Today, op amps are used widely in consumer, industrial, and scientific electronics.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Many standard integrated circuit op amps cost only a few cents; however, some integrated or hybrid operational amplifiers with special performance specifications may cost over US$100.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Op amps may be packaged as components or used as elements of more complex integrated circuits.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The op amp is one type of differential amplifier.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The amplifier's differential inputs consist of a non-inverting input (+) with voltage *V*+ and an inverting input (−) with voltage *V*−; ideally the op amp amplifies only the difference in voltage between the two, which is called the *differential input voltage*.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The output voltage of the op amp *V*out is given by the equation $V_{\text{out}}=A_{\text{OL}}(V_{+}-V_{-}),$ where *A*OL is the open-loop gain of the amplifier (the term "open-loop" refers to the absence of an external feedback loop from the output to the input).
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The magnitude of *A*OL is typically very large (100,000 or more for integrated circuit op amps, corresponding to +100 dB).
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Thus, even small microvolts of difference between *V*+ and *V*− may drive the amplifier into clipping or saturation.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The magnitude of *A*OL is not well controlled by the manufacturing process, and so it is impractical to use an open-loop amplifier as a stand-alone differential amplifier.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Without negative feedback, and optionally positive feedback for regeneration, an *open-loop* op amp acts as a comparator, although comparator ICs are better suited.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] If the inverting input of an ideal op amp is held at ground (0 V), and the input voltage *V*in applied to the non-inverting input is positive, the output will be maximum positive; if *V*in is negative, the output will be maximum negative.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] If predictable operation is desired, negative feedback is used by applying a portion of the output voltage to the inverting input.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The *closed-loop* feedback greatly reduces the gain of the circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] When negative feedback is used, the circuit's overall gain and response are determined primarily by the feedback network, rather than by the op-amp characteristics.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] If the feedback network is made of components with values small relative to the op amp's input impedance, the value of the op amp's open-loop response *A*OL does not seriously affect the circuit's performance.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] In this context, high input impedance at the input terminals and low output impedance at the output terminal(s) are particularly useful features of an op amp.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The response of the op-amp circuit with its input, output, and feedback circuits to an input is characterized mathematically by a transfer function; designing an op-amp circuit to have a desired transfer function is in the realm of electrical engineering.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The transfer functions are important in most applications of op amps, such as in analog computers.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] In the non-inverting amplifier on the right, the presence of negative feedback via the voltage divider *R*f, *R*g determines the *closed-loop gain* *A*CL = *V*out / *V*in.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Equilibrium will be established when *V*out is just sufficient to pull the inverting input to the same voltage as *V*in.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The voltage gain of the entire circuit is thus 1 + *R*f / *R*g.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] As a simple example, if *V*in = 1 V and Rf = *R*g, *V*out will be 2 V, exactly the amount required to keep *V*− at 1 V.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Because of the feedback provided by the *R*f, *R*g network, this is a *closed-loop* circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The input impedance of the (+) and (−) pins is much larger than other resistances in the circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The first rule only applies in the usual case where the op amp is used in a negative feedback design, where there is a signal path of some sort feeding back from the output to the inverting input.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] These rules are commonly used as a good first approximation for analyzing or designing op-amp circuits.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] None of these ideals can be perfectly realized.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] A real op amp may be modeled with non-infinite or non-zero parameters using equivalent resistors and capacitors in the op-amp model.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] The designer can then include these effects in the overall performance of the final circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Some parameters may turn out to have negligible effect on the final design, while others represent actual limitations of the final performance.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Real op amps differ from the ideal model in various aspects.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] is finite in real operational amplifiers.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Typical devices exhibit open-loop DC gain exceeding 100,000.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] (i.e., the product of open-loop and feedback gains) is very large, the closed-loop gain will be determined entirely by the amount of negative feedback (i.e., it will be independent of open-loop gain).
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] In applications where the closed-loop gain must be very high (approaching the open-loop gain), the feedback gain will be very low and the lower loop gain in these cases causes non-ideal behavior from the circuit.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] Low output impedance is important for low-impedance loads; for these loads, the voltage drop across the output impedance effectively reduces the open-loop gain.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] In configurations with a voltage-sensing negative feedback, the output impedance of the amplifier is effectively lowered; thus, in linear applications, op-amp circuits usually exhibit a very low output impedance.
[src:operational-amplifiers/op-amp] in the output stage and will dissipate more power, so low-power designs may purposely sacrifice low output impedance.
